{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/using-git-with-colab-via-ssh-175e8f3751ec", "time": 1682993414.041922, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/using-git-with-colab-via-ssh-175e8f3751ec/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "From Git to Colab, via SSH. SSH to Git from Colab & clone your\u2026 | by Chella Priyadharshini | Towards Data Science", "h1": "From Git to Colab, via SSH", "description": "When you are using Google\u2019s Colaboratory (Colab) for running your Deep Learning models the most obvious way to access the large datasets is by storing them on Google Drive and then mounting Drive\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://techsupportallbugs.wordpress.com/2018/06/05/using-git-with-colab-via-ssh/", "anchor_text": "techsupportallbugs.wordpress.com", "paragraph_index": 14}], "all_paragraphs": ["When you are using Google\u2019s Colaboratory (Colab) for running your Deep Learning models the most obvious way to access the large datasets is by storing them on Google Drive and then mounting Drive onto the Colab environment. But a lot of open sourced large datasets that are available for research purposes, are hosted on Github/Gitlab. Fortunately, Colab provides an easy way to integrate your Github and access your repositories. So, let us see the steps in detail.", "I will explain the integration in case of two scenarios:", "The integration is just a couple of lines \u2014 when the git repository you want to clone is a public one.", "On executing the above 2 lines, you will be prompted to go to the Google Accounts URL as shown, for authenticating. Click on the URL displayed in the Output section of the notebook cell. This takes you to a page like below:", "Click on Allow button. This will take you to the next page where an Authorization code is displayed (where I have struck in red).", "Copy this code and paste it in the cell (as shown in the first image) in the place where it says \u2018Enter your authorization code\u2019, and then click Enter. Google Drive is now mounted and you get the message confirming that.", "You can then set any of your Drive folders as your working directory. Then clone the public git repo in to your working directory. These two steps are implemented as below:", "Unfortunately, you cannot clone your private repositories as easily. As a matter of fact, you can pull off a one-liner in that case as well as shown below:", "That is, provide your username:password along with the repository link to clone a private repository. This works, but the catch is that the password gets stored in git/config and in your bash history logs. Therefore it is not advisable to clone your private repos in the above manner. Instead we will be using the SSH protocol to connect your private github/gitlab repo to colab.", "#Enter the name of the file when prompted: ~/.ssh/id_rsa_<some_name>", "#Enter a passphrase: just press \u2018Enter\u2019 (for no passphrase)", "\u201cYou want to be running ssh-agent in the background as you log in. Once you log in, the idea is to run ssh-add once and only once, in order to give the agent your passphrase, to decode your key. The agent then just sits in memory with your key unlocked and loaded, ready to use every time you ssh somewhere. All ssh-family commands1 will then consult the agent and automatically be able to use your private key.\u201d", "That\u2019s all! We have SSH-ed into our Git account from Colab and cloned our private repository.", "Images of the Logos are Googled. Copyrights belong to Colaboratory and Github respectively. Other images are screenshots of my work.", "Originally published at techsupportallbugs.wordpress.com on June 5, 2018.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F175e8f3751ec&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------",